{"title_page": "Great Russia", "text_new": "{{About|the term|the political party|Great Russia (political party)|other meanings of \"Russia\"|Russia (disambiguation)}}\n{{Also|All-Russian nation}}\n{{Distinguish|Greater Russia|Great Russian}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2016}}\n\n[[Image:Europ\u00e4isches_russland.jpg|thumb|300px|This original German map titled \"{{lang|de|Europ\u00e4isches Russland}}\" (European Russia) published in 1885\u201390 by [[Meyers Konversations-Lexikon]] shows {{lang|de|Gross-Russland}} (literally ''Great Russia'') as the historical region of the Russian Empire. The territory of the Great Russia was practically the same as of the [[Tsardom of Russia]] in the 16th century before the conquest of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]] and [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]] khanates and Siberia.]]\n\n'''Great Russia''', sometimes '''Great [[names of Rus', Russia and Ruthenia|Rus']]''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0443\u0441\u044c}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikaya Rus'}}, {{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikaya Rossiya}}, {{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorossiya}}), is a name formerly applied to the territories of \"Russia proper\", the land that formed the core of [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Muscovy]] and later [[Russia]]. This was the land to which the ethnic [[Russians]] were native and where the ethnogenesis of (Great) Russians took place. The name is said to have come from the [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|el|\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7  \u1fec\u03c9\u03c3(\u03c3)\u03af\u03b1}}, {{lang|el-Latn|Meg\u00e1l\u0113 Rh\u014ds(s)\u00eda}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Vasmer |first=Max |title=Etymological dictionary of the Russian language |publisher=Progress |date=1986 |location=Moscow |page=289 |url=http://etymolog.ruslang.ru/vasmer.php?id=289&vol=1 }}</ref> used by [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] for the northern part of the lands of [[Rus (region)|Rus']].\n\nFrom 1654\u20131721, Russian Tsars adopted the word - their official title included the wording (literal translation): \"The Sovereign of all [[Rus (region)|Rus']]: the Great, [[Little Russia|the Little]], and [[Belarus|the White]]\".\n\nSimilarly, the terms [[Great Russian language]] ({{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorusskiy yazyk}}) and Great Russians ({{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u044b}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorossy}}) were employed by ethnographers and linguists in the 19th century, but have since fallen out of use.\n\nHowever, the area became, together with the [[Idel-Ural|Volga-Ural region]], [[North Caucasus]] and [[Siberia]], the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], while [[Little Russia]] and [[Belarus|White Russia]] became the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]] and the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]] respectively.\n\n== Related topics ==\n* [[Names of Rus', Russia and Ruthenia#From Rus' to Russia|Etymology of Rus and derivatives: From Rus' to Rossiya]]\n* [[Greater Poland]]\n* [[Little Russia]]\n* [[Novorossiya|Novorossiya (New Russia)]]\n* [[White Russia|White Russia (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Place name etymologies|Rus]]\n[[Category:Geographic history of Russia]]\n[[Category:History of Ruthenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the term|the political party|Great Russia (political party)|other meanings of \"Russia\"|Russia (disambiguation)}}\n{{Also|All-Russian nation}}\n{{Distinguish|Greater Russia|Great Russian}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=September 2016}}\n\n[[Image:Europ\u00e4isches_russland.jpg|thumb|300px|This original German map titled \"{{lang|de|Europ\u00e4isches Russland}}\" (European Russia) published in 1885\u201390 by [[Meyers Konversations-Lexikon]] shows {{lang|de|Gross-Russland}} (literally ''Great Russia'') as the historical region of the Russian Empire. The territory of the Great Russia was practically the same as of the [[Tsardom of Russia]] in the 16th century before the conquest of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]] and [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]] khanates and Siberia.]]\n\n'''Great Russia''', sometimes '''Great [[names of Rus', Russia and Ruthenia|Rus']]''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0443\u0441\u044c}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikaya Rus'}}, {{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikaya Rossiya}}, {{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorossiya}}), is a name formerly applied to the territories of \"Russia proper\", the land that formed the core of [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Muscovy]] and later [[Russia]]. This was the land to which the ethnic [[Russians]] were native and where the ethnogenesis of (Great) Russians took place. The name is said to have come from the [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|el|\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7  \u1fec\u03c9\u03c3(\u03c3)\u03af\u03b1}}, {{lang|el-Latn|Meg\u00e1l\u0113 Rh\u014ds(s)\u00eda}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Vasmer |first=Max |title=Etymological dictionary of the Russian language |publisher=Progress |date=1986 |location=Moscow |page=289 |url=http://etymolog.ruslang.ru/vasmer.php?id=289&vol=1 }}</ref> used by [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] for the northern part of the lands of [[Rus (region)|Rus']].\n\nFrom 1654\u20131721, Russian Tsars adopted the word - their official title included the wording (literal translation): \"The Sovereign of all [[Rus (region)|Rus']]: the Great, [[Little Russia|the Little]], and [[Belarus|the White]]\".\n\nSimilarly, the terms [[Great Russian language]] ({{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorusskiy yazyk}}) and Great Russians ({{lang|ru|\u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u044b}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Velikorossy}}) were employed by ethnographers and linguists in the 19th century, but have since fallen out of use.\n\nHowever, the area became, together with the [[Idel-Ural|Volga-Ural region]], [[North Caucasus]] and [[Siberia]], the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], while [[Little Russia]] and [[Belarus|White Russia]] became the [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian SSR]] and the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]] respectively.\n\n== Related topics ==\n* [[Names of Rus', Russia and Ruthenia#From Rus' to Russia|Etymology of Rus and derivatives: From Rus' to Rossiya]]\n* [[Greater Poland]]\n* [[Little Russia]]\n* [[Novorossiya|New Russia]]\n* [[White Russia|White Russia (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Place name etymologies|Rus]]\n[[Category:Geographic history of Russia]]\n[[Category:History of Ruthenia]]\n", "name_user": "Kenwick", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Russia"}
