outh Horizons Station.jpg|100px]] ||  || rowspan=\"4\" | [[Southern District (Hong Kong)|Southern]] || rowspan=\"5\" | 28 December 2016 || SOH\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF7F00;\"| || [[Lei Tung station|Lei Tung]] || [[File:Platform 2 of Lei Tung Station.jpg|100px]] ||  || LET\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"| || [[Wong Chuk Hang station|Wong Chuk Hang]] || [[File:Platform 2 of Wong Chuk Hang Station.jpg|100px]] ||  || WCH\n|-\n| style=\"background:#00BFFF;\"| || [[Ocean Park station (MTR)|Ocean Park]] || [[File:Platform 1 of Ocean Park Station.jpg|100px]] ||  || OCP\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"| || [[Admiralty station (MTR)|Admiralty]] || [[File:Platform 5 of Admiralty Station.jpg|100px]] || {{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}}<br />{{rcb|MTR|Island|yes}} || [[Central and Western District|Central and Western]] || ADM\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{portal-inline|Hong Kong}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mtr.com.hk/jplanner/images/maps/routemap.pdf MTR Route Map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071007153839/http://www.theskytrain.net/hkmtr/Past_History.htm MTR \u2013 The Past]\n\n{{MTRStations}}\n{{MTR}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MTR}}\n[[Category:Hong Kong transport-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of metro stations]]\n[[Category:MTR stations|*]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Lists of railway stations in China]]\n", "name_user": "2406:3003:2002:190c:3876:4f14:946c:d689", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTsuen Wan Line)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_MTR_stations"}
{"title_page": "Neural crest", "text_new": "{{short description|Embyronic group of cells giving rise to diverse cell lineages}}\n{{Infobox embryology\n|Name         = Neural crest \n|Image        = Neural crest.svg \n|Caption      = The formation of neural crest during the process of neurulation. Neural crest is first induced in the region of the [[neural plate]] border. After [[neural tube]] closure, neural crest delaminates from the region between the dorsal neural tube and overlying [[ectoderm]] and migrates out towards the periphery.\n|Image2       =\n|Caption2     =\n}}\n'''Neural crest''' cells are a temporary group of cells unique to [[vertebrate]]s that arise from the embryonic [[ectoderm]] [[germ layer]], and in turn give rise to a diverse cell lineage\u2014including [[melanocytes]], [[craniofacial]] cartilage and bone, [[smooth muscle]], [[Peripheral nervous system|peripheral]] and [[enteric neuron]]s and [[glia]].<ref name=\"SJ04\">{{cite journal | last1 = Huang | first1 = X. | last2 = Saint-Jeannet | first2 = J.P. | year = 2004 | title = Induction of the neural crest and the opportunities of life on the edge | url = | journal = Dev. Biol. | volume = 275 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201311 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2004.07.033 | pmid = 15464568 }}</ref><ref name=\"Shakhova\">{{cite journal |last1=Shakhova |first1=Olga |last2=Sommer |first2=Lukas |title=Neural crest-derived stem cells |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44752/ |journal=StemBook |publisher=Harvard Stem Cell Institute |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=2008|doi=10.3824/stembook.1.51.1 |pmid=20614636 }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[gastrulation]], neural crest cells are specified at the border of the [[neural plate]] and the non-neural [[ectoderm]].  During [[neurulation]], the borders of the neural plate, also known as the [[neural fold]]s, converge at the dorsal midline to form the [[neural tube]].<ref>Brooker, R.J. 2014, Biology, 3rd edn, McGraw-Hill, New York, NY, 1084</ref> Subsequently, neural crest cells from the roof plate of the neural tube undergo an [[Epithelial-mesenchymal transition|epithelial to mesenchymal transition]], delaminating from the [[neuroepithelial cell|neuroepithelium]] and migrating through the periphery where they differentiate into varied cell types.<ref name=\"SJ04\"/> The emergence of neural crest was important in [[vertebrate]] evolution because many of its structural derivatives are defining features of the vertebrate [[clade]].<ref name=\"BF04\">{{cite journal | last1 = Meulemans | first1 = D. | last2 = Bronner-Fraser | first2 = M. | year = 2004 | title = Gene-regulatory interactions in neural crest evolution and development | url = | journal = Dev Cell | volume = 7 | issue = 3| pages = 291\u20139 | doi = 10.1016/j.devcel.2004.08.007 | pmid = 15363405 }}</ref> \n \nUnderlying the development of neural crest is a [[gene regulatory network]], described as a set of interacting signals, [[transcription factors]], and downstream [[effector (biology)|effector]] genes that confer cell characteristics such as multipotency and migratory capabilities.<ref name=\"BF07\">{{cite journal | last1 = Sauka-Spengler | first1 = T. | last2 = Meulemans | first2 = D. | last3 = Jones | first3 = M. | last4 = Bronner-Fraser | first4 = M. | year = 2007 | title = Ancient evolutionary origin of the neural crest gene regulatory network | url = | journal = Dev Cell | volume = 13 | issue = 3| pages = 405\u201320 | doi = 10.1016/j.devcel.2007.08.005 | pmid = 17765683 }}</ref> Understanding the molecular mechanisms of neural crest formation is important for our knowledge of human disease because of its contributions to multiple [[cell lineage]]s. Abnormalities in neural crest development cause [[neurocristopathy|neurocristopathies]], which include conditions such as [[frontonasal dysplasia]], [[Waardenburg\u2013Shah syndrome]], and [[DiGeorge syndrome]].<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>\n\nTherefore, defining the mechanisms of neural crest development may reveal key insights into vertebrate evolution and neurocristopathies.\n\n==History==\nNeural crest was first described in the chick embryo by [[Wilhelm His Sr.]] in 1868 as \"the cord in between\" (Zwischenstrang) because of its origin between the neural plate and non-neural ectoderm.<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>  He named the tissue ganglionic crest since its final destination was each lateral side of the neural tube where it differentiated into spinal ganglia.<ref name=\"douarin\">{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 2004 | title = The avian embryo as a model to study the development of the neural crest: a long and still ongoing story | url = | journal = Mech. Dev. | volume = 121 | issue = 9| pages = 1089\u2013102 | doi = 10.1016/j.mod.2004.06.003 | pmid = 15296974 }}</ref> During the first half of the 20th century the majority of research on neural crest was done using amphibian embryos which was reviewed by H\u00f6rstadius (1950) in a well known monograph.<ref>[[Sven H\u00f6rstadius|H\u00f6rstadius]], S. (1950). ''The Neural Crest: Its Properties and Derivatives in the Light of Experimental Research''. Oxford University Press, London, 111 p.</ref>\n \nCell labeling techniques advanced the field of neural crest because they allowed researchers to visualize the migration of the tissue throughout the developing embryos.  In the 1960s Weston and Chibon utilized radioisotopic labeling of the nucleus with tritiated thymidine in chick and amphibian embryo respectively.  However, this method suffers from drawbacks of stability, since every time the labeled cell divides the signal is diluted.  Modern cell labeling techniques such as rhodamine-lysinated dextran and the vital dye diI have also been developed to transiently mark neural crest lineages.<ref name=\"douarin\"/>\n\nThe quail-chick marking system, devised by Nicole Le Douarin in 1969, was another instrumental technique used to track neural crest cells.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 1969 | title = Particularit\u00e9s du noyau interphasique chez la Caille japonaise (Coturnix coturnix japonica). Utilisation de ces particularit\u00e9s comme \"marquage biologique\" dans les recherches sur les interactions tissulaires et les migrations cellulaires au cours de l'ontogen\u00e8se\" | url = | journal = Bull Biol Fr Belg | volume = 103 | issue = 3| pages = 435\u201352 | pmid = 4191116 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 1973 | title = A biological cell labeling technique and its use in experimental embryology | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 30 | issue = 1| pages = 217\u201322 | doi = 10.1016/0012-1606(73)90061-4 | pmid = 4121410 }}</ref> [[Chimera (genetics)|Chimera]]s, generated through transplantation, enabled researchers to distinguish neural crest cells of one species from the surrounding tissue of another species.  With this technique, generations of scientists were able to reliably mark and study the [[ontogeny]] of neural crest cells.\n\n==Induction==\nA molecular cascade of events is involved in establishing the migratory and multipotent characteristics of neural crest cells.  This [[gene regulatory network]] can be subdivided into the following four sub-networks described below.\n\n===Inductive signals===\nFirst, extracellular signaling molecules, secreted from the adjacent [[epidermis]] and underlying [[mesoderm]] such as [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnts]], [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMPs]] and [[Fibroblast growth factor|Fgfs]] separate the non-neural [[ectoderm]] (epidermis) from the neural plate during [[neural induction]].<ref name=\"SJ04\"/><ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n\nWnt signaling has been demonstrated in neural crest induction in several species through gain-of-function and loss-of-function experiments. In coherence with this observation, the [[promoter (genetics)|promoter]] region of slug (a neural crest specific gene) contains a [[binding site]] for [[transcription factor]]s involved in the activation of Wnt-dependent target genes, suggestive of a direct role of Wnt signaling in neural crest specification.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vallin | first1 = J. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2001 | title = Cloning and characterization of the three Xenopus slug promoters reveal direct regulation by Lef/beta-catenin signaling | url = | journal = J Biol Chem | volume = 276 | issue = 32| pages = 30350\u20138 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M103167200 | pmid=11402039}}</ref>\n\nThe current role of BMP in neural crest formation is associated with the induction of the neural plate.  BMP antagonists diffusing from the ectoderm generates a gradient of BMP activity. In this manner, the neural crest lineage forms from intermediate levels of BMP signaling required for the development of the neural plate (low BMP) and epidermis (high BMP).<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>\n\nFgf from the [[paraxial mesoderm]] has been suggested as a source of neural crest inductive signal.  Researchers have demonstrated that the expression of dominate-negative Fgf receptor in ectoderm explants blocks neural crest induction when recombined with paraxial mesoderm.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mayor | first1 = R. | last2 = Guerrero | first2 = N. | last3 = Martinez | first3 = C. | year = 1997 | title = Role of FGF and noggin in neural crest induction | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 189 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201312 | doi = 10.1006/dbio.1997.8634 | pmid = 9281332 }}</ref> The understanding of the role of BMP, Wnt, and Fgf pathways on neural crest specifier expression remains incomplete.\n\n===Neural plate border specifiers===\nSignaling events that establish the neural plate border lead to the expression of a set of transcription factors delineated here as neural plate border specifiers.  These molecules include Zic factors, Pax3/7, Dlx5, Msx1/2 which may mediate the influence of Wnts, BMPs, and Fgfs.  These genes are expressed broadly at the neural plate border region and precede the expression of bona fide neural crest markers.<ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n\nExperimental evidence places these transcription factors upstream of neural crest specifiers.  For example, in ''[[Xenopus]]'' Msx1 is [[necessary and sufficient]] for the expression of Slug, Snail, and FoxD3.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tribulo | first1 = C. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2003 | title = Regulation of Msx genes by Bmp gradient is essential for neural crest specification | url = | journal = Development | volume = 130 | issue = 26| pages = 6441\u201352 | doi = 10.1242/dev.00878 | pmid=14627721}}</ref> Furthermore, Pax3 is essential for FoxD3 expression in mouse embryos.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dottori | first1 = M. | last2 = Gross | first2 = M.K. | last3 = Labosky | first3 = P. | last4 = Goulding | first4 = M. | year = 2001 | title = The winged-helix transcription factor Foxd3 suppresses interneuron differentiation and promotes neural crest cell fate | url = | journal = Development | volume = 128 | issue = 21| pages = 4127\u20134138 | pmid = 11684651 }}</ref>\n\n===Neural crest specifiers===\nFollowing the expression of neural plate border specifiers is a collection of genes including Slug/Snail, FoxD3, Sox10, Sox9, AP-2 and c-Myc.  This suite of genes, designated here as neural crest specifiers, are activated in emergent neural crest cells.  At least in Xenopus, every neural crest specifier is necessary and/or sufficient for the expression of all other specifiers, demonstrating the existence of extensive cross-regulation.<ref name=\"BF04\"/> Moreover, this model organism was instrumental in the elucidation of the role of the Hedghehog signaling pathway in the specification of the neural crest, with the transcription factor Gli2 playing a key role.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cerrizuela|first=Santiago|last2=Vega-L\u00f3pez|first2=Guillermo A.|last3=Palacio|first3=Mar\u00eda Bel\u00e9n|last4=Tr\u00edbulo|first4=Celeste|last5=Aybar|first5=Manuel J.|date=2018-12-01|title=Gli2 is required for the induction and migration of Xenopus laevis neural crest|journal=Mechanisms of Development|volume=154|pages=219\u2013239|doi=10.1016/j.mod.2018.07.010|pmid=30086335|issn=0925-4773}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the tightly regulated network of neural crest specifiers are two other transcription factors Twist and Id.  Twist, a [[bHLH]] transcription factor, is required for mesenchyme differentiation of the [[pharyngeal arch]] structures.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vincentz | first1 = J.W. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2008 | title = An absence of Twist1 results in aberrant cardiac neural crest morphogenesis | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 320 | issue = 1| pages = 131\u20139 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2008.04.037 | pmid = 18539270 | pmc = 2572997 }}</ref> Id is a direct target of c-Myc and is known to be important for the maintenance of neural crest stem cells.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Light | first1 = W. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2005 | title = Xenopus Id3 is required downstream of Myc for the formation of multipotent neural crest progenitor cells | url = | journal = Development | volume = 132 | issue = 8| pages = 1831\u201341 | doi = 10.1242/dev.01734 | pmid=15772131}}</ref>\n\n===Neural crest effector genes===\nFinally, neural crest specifiers turn on the expression of effector genes, which confer certain properties such as migration and multipotency. Two neural crest effectors, ''[[Rho family of GTPases|Rho GTPases]]'' and ''[[cadherins]]'', function in delamination by regulating cell morphology and adhesive properties.  Sox9 and Sox10 regulate neural crest differentiation by activating many cell-type-specific effectors including Mitf, P0, Cx32, Trp and cKit.<ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n[[Image:GRN Crest.png|thumb|center|700px|alt=Neural Crest.|Putative neural crest gene-regulatory network functioning at the neural plate border in vertebrates. Red arrows represent proven direct regulatory interactions.  Black arrows show genetic interactions based on loss-of-function and gain-of-functions studies.  Gray lines denote repression.  Adapted from Bronner-Fraser 2004]]\n\n== Migration ==\n{{Further|Collective cell migration}}\n[[File:Neural Crest Cell Delamination .tif|thumb|Delamination of neural crest cells during development. Downregulation of CAMs and tight junction proteins is followed by secretion of MMPs and subsequent delamination.]]\nThe migration of neural crest cells involves a highly coordinated cascade of events that begins with closure of the [[Anatomical terms of location|dorsal]] [[neural tube]].\n\n=== Delamination ===\nAfter fusion of the [[neural fold]] to create the [[neural tube]], cells originally located in the [[neural plate]] border become neural crest [[Cell (biology)|cells]].<ref name=\":0\" /> For migration to begin, neural crest cells must undergo a process called delamination that involves a full or partial [[Epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT)]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Lamouille|first=Samy|year=2014|title=Molecular mechanisms of epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|pmc=4240281|journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology|volume=15|issue=3|pages=178\u2013196|pmid=24556840|doi=10.1038/nrm3758}}</ref> Delamination is defined as the separation of [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]] into different populations, in this case neural crest cells separating from the surrounding tissue.<ref name=\":1\" /> Conversely, EMT is a series of events coordinating a change from an [[Epithelium|epithelial]] to [[Mesenchymal stem cell|mesenchymal]] [[phenotype]].<ref name=\":4\" /> For example, delamination in [[Chicken|chick]] [[embryo]]s is triggered by a [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMP]]/[[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt]] [[Signal transduction|cascade]] that induces the expression of EMT promoting [[transcription factor]]s such as [[SNAI2]] and [[FOXD3|FoxD3]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Although all neural crest cells undergo EMT, the timing of delamination occurs at different stages in different organisms: in [[African clawed frog|''Xenopus laevis'']] embryos there is a massive delamination that occurs when the [[neural plate]] is not entirely fused, whereas delamination in the [[Chicken|chick]] embryo occurs during fusion of the [[neural fold]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Theveneau|first=Eric|year=2012|title=Neural crest delamination and migration: From epithelium-to-mesenchyme transition to collective cell migration|journal=Developmental Biology|volume=366|issue=1|pages=34\u201354|doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.12.041|pmid=22261150|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1337167/2/1337167.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPrior to delamination, presumptive neural crest cells are initially anchored to neighboring cells by [[tight junction]] proteins such as [[occludin]] and [[cell adhesion molecule]]s such as [[Neural cell adhesion molecule|NCAM]] and [[CDH2|N''-''Cadherin]].<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Anatomical terms of location|Dorsally]] expressed [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMPs]] initiate delamination by inducing the expression of the [[zinc finger]] protein transcription factors [[SNAI1|snail]], [[SNAI2|slug]], and [[Twist transcription factor|twist]].<ref name=\":0\" /> These factors play a direct role in inducing the [[Epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|epithelial-mesenchymal transition]] by reducing expression of [[occludin]] and [[CDH2|N-Cadherin]] in addition to promoting [[Post-translational modification|modification]] of [[Neural cell adhesion molecule|NCAMs]] with [[polysialic acid]] residues to decrease adhesiveness.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Neural crest cells also begin expressing [[protease]]s capable of degrading [[cadherin]]s such as [[ADAM10]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mayor|first=Roberto|year=2013|title=The Neural Crest|journal=Development|volume=140|issue=11|pages=2247\u20132251|doi=10.1242/dev.091751|pmid=23674598}}</ref> and secreting [[Matrix metalloproteinase|matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs)]] that degrade the overlying [[basal lamina]] of the neural tube to allow neural crest cells to escape.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, neural crest cells begin expressing [[integrin]]s that associate with [[extracellular matrix]] proteins, including [[collagen]], [[fibronectin]], and [[laminin]], during migration.<ref name=\":3\" /> Once the basal lamina becomes permeable the neural crest cells can begin migrating throughout the embryo.\n\n=== Migration ===\n[[File:Migration of Neural Crest Cells (v2).jpg|alt=|thumb|Migration of neural crest cells during development. Grey arrows indicate the direction of the paths crest cells migrate. (R=Rostral, C=Caudal)]]\nNeural crest cell migration occurs in a [[Anatomical terms of location|rostral]] to [[Anatomical terms of location|caudal]] direction without the need of a neuronal [[Scaffold/matrix attachment region|scaffold]] such as along a [[radial glial cell]]. For this reason the crest cell migration process is termed \u201cfree migration\u201d. Instead of scaffolding on [[progenitor cell]]s, neural crest migration is the result of repulsive guidance via [[EPHB3|EphB]]/[[Ephrin receptor|EphrinB]] and [[SEMA4D|semaphorin]]/[[neuropilin]]  signaling, interactions with the [[extracellular matrix]], and [[contact inhibition]] with one another.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Development of the Nervous System, 3rd ed|last=Sanes|first=Dan|publisher=ELSEVIER INC.|year=2012|isbn=978-0123745392|location=Oxford|pages=70\u201372}}</ref> While Ephrin and Eph proteins have the capacity to undergo bi-directional signaling, neural crest cell repulsion employs predominantly forward signaling to initiate a response within the [[Receptor (biochemistry)|receptor]] bearing neural crest cell.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Sakuka-Spengler|first=Tatjana|year=2008|title=A gene regulatory network orchestrates neural crest formation|doi=10.1038/nrm2428|pmid=18523435|journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology|volume=9|issue=7|pages=557\u2013568}}</ref> Burgeoning neural crest cells express EphB, a [[receptor tyrosine kinase]], which binds the EphrinB transmembrane [[Ligand (biochemistry)|ligand]] expressed in the caudal half of each [[somite]]. When these two domains interact it causes receptor tyrosine phosphorylation, activation of [[Rho family of GTPases|rhoGTPases]], and eventual [[Cytoskeleton|cytoskeletal]] rearrangements within the crest cells inducing them to repel. This phenomenon allows neural crest cells to funnel through the rostral portion of each somite.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSemaphorin-neuropilin repulsive signaling works synergistically with EphB signaling to guide neural crest cells down the rostral half of somites in mice. In chick embryos, semaphorin acts in the cephalic region to guide neural crest cells through the [[pharyngeal arch]]es. On top of repulsive repulsive signaling, neural crest cells express \u03b21and \u03b14 [[integrin]]s which allows for binding and guided interaction with [[collagen]], [[laminin]], and [[fibronectin]] of the extracellular matrix as they travel. Additionally, crest cells have intrinsic contact inhibition with one another while freely invading tissues of different origin such as [[mesoderm]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Neural crest cells that migrate through the rostral half of somites differentiate into [[Sensory neuron|sensory]] and [[Sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] neurons of the [[peripheral nervous system]]. The other main route neural crest cells take is [[Anatomical terms of location|dorsolaterally]] between the [[epidermis]] and the [[Dermatome (embryology)|dermamyotome]]. Cells migrating through this path differentiate into [[Melanocyte|pigment cells]] of the [[dermis]]. Further neural crest cell [[Cellular differentiation|differentiation]] and specification into their final cell type is biased by their [[Spatiotemporal gene expression|spatiotemporal]] subjection to morphogenic cues such as BMP, Wnt, FGF, [[Hox gene|Hox]], and [[Notch signaling pathway|Notch]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of Neural Science|last=Kandel|first=Eric|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.|year=2013|isbn=978-0-07-139011-8|location=New York|pages=1197\u20131199}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical significance==\n[[Neurocristopathies]] result from the abnormal specification, migration, differentiation or death of neural crest cells throughout embryonic development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vega-Lopez|first=Guillermo A.|last2=Cerrizuela|first2=Santiago|last3=Tribulo|first3=Celeste|last4=Aybar|first4=Manuel J.|date=2018-12-01|title=Neurocristopathies: New insights 150 years after the neural crest discovery|journal=Developmental Biology|series=The Neural Crest: 150 years after His' discovery|volume=444|pages=S110\u2013S143|doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2018.05.013|pmid=29802835|issn=0012-1606}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bolande|first=Robert P.|date=1974-07-01|title=The neurocristopathies: A unifying concept of disease arising in neural crest maldevelopment|journal=Human Pathology|volume=5|issue=4|pages=409\u2013429|doi=10.1016/S0046-8177(74)80021-3|issn=0046-8177}}</ref> This group of diseases comprises a wide spectrum of congenital malformations affecting many newborns. Additionally, they arise because of genetic defects affecting the formation of neural crest and because of the action of [[Teratogen]]s <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cerrizuela|first=Santiago|last2=Vega\u2010Lopez|first2=Guillermo A.|last3=Aybar|first3=Manuel J.|date=2020-01-11|title=The role of teratogens in neural crest development|journal=Birth Defects Research|language=en|pages=bdr2.1644|doi=10.1002/bdr2.1644|pmid=31926062|issn=2472-1727}}</ref>\n\n====Waardenburg's syndrome====\n[[Waardenburg syndrome|Waardenburg's syndrome]] is a [[neurocristopathy]] that results from defective neural crest cell migration. The condition's main characteristics include [[piebaldism]] and [[Congenital hearing loss|congenital deafness]]. In the case of piebaldism, the colorless [[skin]] areas are caused by a total absence of neural crest-derived [[Biological pigment|pigment]]-producing [[melanocyte]]s.<ref name=\":x\">{{cite journal | last1 = Mallory | first1 = S.B. | last2 = Wiener | first2 = E | last3 = Nordlund | first3 = J.J. | year = 1986 | title = Waardenburg's Syndrome with Hirschprung's Disease: A Neural Crest Defect | url = | journal = Pediatric Dermatology | volume = 3 | issue = 2| pages = 119\u2013124 | pmid = 3952027 | doi = 10.1111/j.1525-1470.1986.tb00501.x }}</ref> There are four different types of Waardenburg's syndrome, each with distinct [[Genetics|genetic]] and physiological features. Types I and II are distinguished based on whether or not family members of the affected individual have [[Canthus#Pathology|dystopia canthorum]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Arias | first1 = S | year = 1971 | title = Genetic heterogeneity in the Waardenburg's syndrome | url = | journal = Birth Defects B | volume =  07| issue = | pages =  87\u2013101| pmid = 5006208 }}</ref> Type III gives rise to upper limb abnormalities. Lastly, type IV is also known as Waardenburg-Shah syndrome, and afflicted individuals display both Waardenburg's syndrome and [[Hirschsprung's disease]].<ref>\"Waardenburg syndrome\". Genetics Home Reference. October 2012.</ref> Types I and III are [[Heredity|inherited]] in an [[Genetic disorder#Autosomal dominant|autosomal dominant]] fashion,<ref name=\":x\" /> while II and IV exhibit an [[Genetic disorder#Autosomal recessive|autosomal recessive]] pattern of inheritance. Overall, Waardenburg's syndrome is rare, with an [[Incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]] of ~ 2/100,000 people in the United States. All [[Race (human categorization)|races]] and [[sex]]es are equally affected.<ref name=\":x\" /> There is no current cure or treatment for Waardenburg's syndrome.\n\n====Hirschsprung's Disease====\n\nAlso implicated in defects related to neural crest cell development and [[cellular migration|migration]] is [[Hirschsprung's disease]] (HD or HSCR), characterized by a lack of innervation in regions of the [[intestine]]. This lack of [[innervation]] can lead to further [[physiological]] abnormalities like an enlarged [[large intestine|colon]] ([[megacolon]]), obstruction of the [[bowels]], or even slowed growth. In healthy development, neural crest cells migrate into the [[gastrointestinal tract|gut]] and form the [[myenteric plexus|enteric ganglia]]. Genes playing a role in the healthy migration of these neural crest cells to the gut include [[RET proto-oncogene|RET]], [[GDNF]], [[GFR\u03b1]], [[EDN3]], and [[EDNRB]]. [[RET proto-oncogene|RET]], a [[receptor tyrosine kinase]] (RTK), forms a complex with [[GDNF]] and [[GFR\u03b1]]. [[EDN3]] and [[EDNRB]] are then implicated in the same signaling network. When this signaling is disrupted in mice, [[aganglionosis]], or the lack of these enteric ganglia occurs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rogers | first1 = J. M. | year = 2016 | title = Search for the missing lncs: gene regulatory networks in neural crest development and long non-coding RNA biomarkers of Hirschsprung's disease | url = | journal = Neurogastroenterol Motil | volume = 28 | issue = 2| pages = 161\u2013166 }}</ref>\n\n====Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder====\n\n[[Alcohol and Pregnancy|Prenatal alcohol exposure]] (PAE) is among the most common causes of [[Birth defect|developmental defects]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sampson | first1 = P. D. | last2 = Streissguth | first2 = A. P. | last3 = Bookstein | first3 = F. L. | last4 = Little | first4 = R. E. | last5 = Clarren | first5 = S. K. | last6 = Dehaene | first6 = P. | last7 = Graham | first7 = J. M. Jr | year = 1997 | title = The incidence of fetal alcohol syndrome and prevalence of the alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder | url = | journal = Teratology | volume = 56 | issue = 5| pages = 317\u2013326 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1096-9926(199711)56:5<317::AID-TERA5>3.0.CO;2-U }}</ref> Depending on the extent of the exposure and the severity of the resulting abnormalities, [[patients]] are diagnosed within a continuum of disorders broadly labeled [[Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder]] (FASD). Severe FASD can impair neural crest [[Cell migration|migration]], as evidenced by characteristic [[craniofacial abnormalities]] including short [[palpebral fissures]], an elongated upper lip, and a smoothened [[philtrum]]. However, due to the promiscuous nature of [[ethanol]] [[Molecular binding|binding]], the mechanisms by which these abnormalities arise is still unclear. [[Cell culture]] [[Explant culture|explants]] of neural crest cells as well as [[in vivo]] developing [[zebrafish]] [[embryos]] exposed to ethanol show a decreased number of [[Cell Migration|migratory cells]] and decreased distances travelled by migrating neural crest cells. The mechanisms behind these changes are not well understood, but evidence suggests PAE can increase [[apoptosis]] due to increased [[cytosol]]ic [[calcium]] levels caused by [[Inositol trisphosphate|IP3]]-mediated [[Calcium signalling|release of calcium]] from [[intracellular]] stores. It has also been proposed that the decreased viability of ethanol-exposed neural crest cells is caused by increased [[oxidative stress]]. Despite these, and other advances much remains to be discovered about how ethanol affects neural crest development. For example, it appears that ethanol differentially affects certain neural crest cells over others; that is, while craniofacial abnormalities are common in PAE, neural crest-derived [[Melanocyte|pigment cells]] appear to be minimally affected.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Smith | first1 = S. M. | last2 = Garic | first2 = A. | last3 = Flentke | first3 = G. R. | last4 = Berres | first4 = M. E. | year = 2014 | title = Neural crest development in fetal alcohol syndrome | url = | journal = Birth Defects Res C Embryo Today | volume = 102 | issue = 3| pages = 210\u2013220 | doi = 10.1002/bdrc.21078 }}</ref>\n\n====DiGeorge syndrome====\n[[DiGeorge syndrome]] is associated with [[Deletion (genetics)|deletions]] or [[translocations]] of a small segment in the [[human]] [[chromosome 22]]. This deletion may disrupt rostral neural crest [[cell migration]] or [[Human embryonic development|development]]. Some defects observed are linked to the [[pharyngeal pouch (embryology)|pharyngeal pouch]] system, which receives contribution from rostral migratory crest cells. The [[symptoms]] of DiGeorge syndrome include [[congenital heart defects]], [[birth defects|facial defects]], and some [[neurological]] and [[learning disabilities]]. Patients with 22q11 deletions have also been reported to have higher incidence of [[schizophrenia]] and [[bipolar disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scambler | first1 = Peter J. | year = 2000 | title = The 22q11 deletion syndromes | url = | journal = Human Molecular Genetics | volume = 9 | issue = 16| pages = 2421\u20132426 | pmid = 11005797 }}</ref>\n\n====Treacher Collins Syndrome====\n[[Treacher Collins Syndrome]] (TCS) results from the compromised development of the first and second [[pharyngeal arches]] during the early embryonic stage, which ultimately leads to mid and lower face abnormalities. TCS is caused by the [[missense mutation]] of the [[TCOF1]] gene, which causes neural crest cells to undergo [[apoptosis]] during [[embryogenesis]]. Although [[mutations]] of the TCOF1 gene are among the best characterized in their role in TCS, mutations in [[POLR1C]] and [[POLR1D]] [[genes]] have also been linked to the [[pathogenesis]] of TCS.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ahmed | first1 = M. | last2 = Ye | first2 = X. | last3 = Taub | first3 = P. | year = 2016 | title = Review of the Genetic Basis of Jaw Malformations | url = http://doi.org/10.1055/s-0036-1593505 | journal = Journal of Pediatric Genetics | volume = 05 | issue = 04| pages = 209\u2013219 | doi = 10.1055/s-0036-1593505 }}</ref>\n\n==Cell lineages==\nNeural crest cells originating from different positions along the [[anterior]]-posterior axis develop into various tissues.  These regions of neural crest can be divided into four main functional domains, which include the cranial neural crest, trunk neural crest, vagal and sacral neural crest, and cardiac neural crest.\n\n===Cranial neural crest===\n{{Main|cranial neural crest}}\n\nCranial neural crest migrates dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various cranial ganglia and craniofacial cartilages and bones.<ref name=\":5\">Taneyhill, L.A. (2008). \"To adhere or not to adhere: the role of Cadherins in neural crest development\". Cell Adh Migr. 2, 223\u201330.</ref> These cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they contribute to the [[thymus]], bones of the middle ear and jaw and the [[odontoblasts]] of the tooth primordia.<ref name=\"gilbert\">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bookshelf/br.fcgi?book=dbio&part=A3109#A3133</ref>\n\n===Trunk neural crest===\n{{Main|trunk neural crest}}\n\nTrunk neural crest gives rise  two populations of cells.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vega-Lopez|first=Guillermo A.|last2=Cerrizuela|first2=Santiago|last3=Aybar|first3=Manuel J.|date=2017|title=Trunk neural crest cells: formation, migration and beyond|journal=The International Journal of Developmental Biology|language=en|volume=61|issue=1\u20132|pages=5\u201315|doi=10.1387/ijdb.160408gv|pmid=28287247|issn=0214-6282}}</ref>  One group of cells fated to become [[melanocytes]] migrates dorsolaterally into the ectoderm towards the ventral midline.  A second group of cells migrates ventrolaterally through the anterior portion of each [[sclerotome]].  The cells that stay in the sclerotome form the [[dorsal root ganglion|dorsal root ganglia]], whereas those that continue more ventrally form the sympathetic ganglia, [[adrenal medulla]], and the nerves surrounding the aorta.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\n\n===Vagal and sacral neural crest===\nThe vagal and sacral neural crest cells develop into the ganglia of the [[enteric nervous system]] and the parasympathetic ganglia.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\n\n===Cardiac neural crest===\n{{Main|cardiac neural crest}}\n\n[[Cardiac neural crest cells|Cardiac neural crest]] develops into melanocytes, cartilage, connective tissue and neurons of some pharyngeal arches.  Also, this domain gives rise to regions of the heart such as the musculo-connective tissue of the large arteries, and part of the [[septum]], which divides the pulmonary circulation from the aorta.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\nThe semilunar valves of the heart are associated with neural crest cells according to new research.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1007/BF00185519 | volume=182 | issue=3 | title=Association of cephalic neural crest cells with cardiovascular development, particularly that of the semilunar valves | year=1990 | journal=Anatomy and Embryology | last1 = Takamura | first1 = Kazushi | last2 = Okishima | first2 = Takahiro | last3 = Ohdo | first3 = Shozo | last4 = Hayakawa | first4 = Kunio| pages=263\u201372 | pmid=2268069 }}</ref>\n\n==Evolution==\nSeveral structures that distinguish the vertebrates from other chordates are formed from the derivatives of neural crest cells.  In their \"New head\" theory, Gans and Northcut argue that the presence of neural crest was the basis for vertebrate specific features, such as sensory ganglia and cranial skeleton.  Furthermore, the appearance of these features was pivotal in vertebrate evolution because it enabled a predatory lifestyle.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gans | first1 = C. | last2 = Northcutt | first2 = R. G. | year = 1983 | title = Neural crest and the origin of vertebrates: A new head | url = | journal = Science | volume = 220 | issue = 4594| pages = 268\u2013274 | doi = 10.1126/science.220.4594.268 | pmid = 17732898 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Northcutt | first = Glenn | year = 2005 | title = The new head hypothesis revisited | journal =  Journal of Experimental Zoology Part B: Molecular and Developmental Evolution | volume = 304B | issue = 4| pages = 274\u2013297 | doi = 10.1002/jez.b.21063 | pmid = 16003768 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, considering the neural crest a vertebrate innovation does not mean that it arose ''[[wikt:de novo|de novo]]''. Instead, new structures often arise through modification of existing developmental regulatory programs.  For example, regulatory programs may be changed by the [[exaptation|co-option]] of new upstream regulators or by the employment of new downstream gene targets, thus placing existing networks in a novel context.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sauka-Spengler | first1 = T. | last2 = Bronner-Fraser | first2 = M. | year = 2006 | title = Development and evolution of the migratory neural crest: a gene regulatory perspective | url = | journal = Curr Opin Genet Dev | volume = 13 | issue = 4| pages = 360\u20136 | doi = 10.1016/j.gde.2006.06.006 | pmid = 16793256 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Donoghue | first1 = P.C. | last2 = Graham | first2 = A. | last3 = Kelsh | first3 = R.N. | year = 2008 | title = The origin and evolution of the neural crest | url = | journal = BioEssays | volume = 30 | issue = 6| pages = 530\u201341 | doi = 10.1002/bies.20767 | pmid = 18478530 | pmc = 2692079 }}</ref> This idea is supported by [[in situ hybridization]] data that shows the conservation of the neural plate border specifiers in [[protochordate]]s, which suggest that part of the neural crest precursor network was present in a common ancestor to the chordates.<ref name=\"BF07\"/> In some non-vertebrate chordates such as [[tunicates]] a lineage of cells (melanocytes) has been identified, which are similar to neural crest cells in vertebrates. This implies that a rudimentary neural crest existed in a common ancestor of vertebrates and tunicates.<ref name=Abitua2012>{{Cite journal | last1 = Abitua | first1 = P. B. | last2 = Wagner | first2 = E. | last3 = Navarrete | first3 = I. A. | last4 = Levine | first4 = M. | title = Identification of a rudimentary neural crest in a non-vertebrate chordate | doi = 10.1038/nature11589 | journal = Nature | year = 2012 | pmid =  23135395| pmc = 4257486| volume=492 | issue = 7427 | pages=104\u2013107}}</ref>\n\n==Neural crest derivatives==\n'''Ectomesenchyme (also known as Mesectoderm)''':<ref>Kalcheim, C. and Le Douarin, N. M. (1998). The Neural Crest (2nd ed.). Cambridge, U. K.: Cambridge University Press.</ref> [[odontoblasts]], [[dental papilla]]e, the [[chondrocranium]] ([[nasal capsule]], [[Meckel's cartilage]], [[scleral ossicles]], quadrate, articular, hyoid and columella), [[trachea]]l and [[larynx|laryngeal]] cartilage, the [[dermatocranium]] (membranous bones), dorsal fins and the turtle plastron (lower vertebrates), [[pericyte]]s and smooth muscle of branchial arteries and veins, [[tendons]] of ocular and masticatory muscles, [[connective tissue]] of head and neck glands (pituitary, salivary, lachrymal, thymus, thyroid) [[dermis]] and adipose tissue of calvaria, ventral neck and face\n\n'''Endocrine cells''':\n[[chromaffin cell]]s of the adrenal medulla, [[glomus cell]]s type I/II.\n\n'''Peripheral nervous system''':\n[[Sensory neuron]]s and glia of the [[dorsal root ganglia]], cephalic ganglia (VII and in part, V, IX, and X), [[Rohon-Beard cell]]s, some [[Merkel cell]]s in the whisker,<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 19786578 | doi=10.1083/jcb.200907080 | volume=187 | issue=1 | title=Epidermal progenitors give rise to Merkel cells during embryonic development and adult homeostasis | pmc=2762088 | date=October 2009 | journal=J. Cell Biol. | pages=91\u2013100 | last1 = Van Keymeulen | first1 = A | last2 = Mascre | first2 = G | last3 = Youseff | first3 = KK | display-authors = etal  }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 12645929 | volume=253 | issue=2 | title=Neural crest origin of mammalian Merkel cells | date=January 2003 | journal=Dev. Biol. | pages=258\u201363 | last1 = Szeder | first1 = V | last2 = Grim | first2 = M | last3 = Halata | first3 = Z | last4 = Sieber-Blum | first4 = M | doi=10.1016/s0012-1606(02)00015-5}}</ref> \n[[Satellite glial cell]]s of all autonomic and sensory ganglia, [[Schwann cell|Schwann]] cells of all peripheral nerves.\n\n'''Enteric cells''':\n[[Enterochromaffin cells]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lake|first1=JI|last2=Heuckeroth|first2=RO|title=Enteric nervous system development: migration, differentiation, and disease.|journal=American Journal of Physiology. Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology|date=1 July 2013|volume=305|issue=1|pages=G1\u201324|pmid=23639815|doi=10.1152/ajpgi.00452.2012|pmc=3725693}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Melanocyte]]s and iris muscle and pigment cells''', and even associated with some tumors (such as [[melanotic neuroectodermal tumor of infancy]]).\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[First arch syndrome]]\n* [[DGCR2]]\u2014may control neural crest cell migration\n*[[List of human cell types derived from the germ layers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{EmbryologyUNSW|Notes/ncrest}}\n* {{BrainInfo|ancil|445}}\n* [http://www.med.umich.edu/lrc/coursepages/M1/embryology/embryo/images/neural_crest_and_notocord.gif Diagram] at [[University of Michigan]]\n* [http://www.palaeos.com/Vertebrates/Bones/Teeth/Images/ChickNeural%20Crest.gif Hox domains in chicks]\n\n{{embryology}}\n{{Development of nervous system}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Embryology of nervous system]]\n[[Category:Ectoderm]]\n[[Category:Chordates]]\n[[Category:Chordate anatomy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Embyronic group of cells giving rise to diverse cell lineages}}\n{{Infobox embryology\n|Name         = Neural crest \n|Image        = Neural crest.svg \n|Caption      = The formation of neural crest during the process of neurulation. Neural crest is first induced in the region of the [[neural plate]] border. After [[neural tube]] closure, neural crest delaminates from the region between the dorsal neural tube and overlying [[ectoderm]] and migrates out towards the periphery.\n|Image2       =\n|Caption2     =\n}}\n'''Neural crest''' cells are a temporary group of cells unique to [[vertebrate]]s that arise from the embryonic [[ectoderm]] [[germ layer]], and in turn give rise to a diverse cell lineage\u2014including [[melanocytes]], [[craniofacial]] cartilage and bone, [[smooth muscle]], [[Peripheral nervous system|peripheral]] and [[enteric neuron]]s and [[glia]].<ref name=\"SJ04\">{{cite journal | last1 = Huang | first1 = X. | last2 = Saint-Jeannet | first2 = J.P. | year = 2004 | title = Induction of the neural crest and the opportunities of life on the edge | url = | journal = Dev. Biol. | volume = 275 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201311 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2004.07.033 | pmid = 15464568 }}</ref><ref name=\"Shakhova\">{{cite journal |last1=Shakhova |first1=Olga |last2=Sommer |first2=Lukas |title=Neural crest-derived stem cells |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44752/ |journal=StemBook |publisher=Harvard Stem Cell Institute |accessdate=27 December 2019 |date=2008|doi=10.3824/stembook.1.51.1 |pmid=20614636 }}</ref>\n\nAfter [[gastrulation]], neural crest cells are specified at the border of the [[neural plate]] and the non-neural [[ectoderm]].  During [[neurulation]], the borders of the neural plate, also known as the [[neural fold]]s, converge at the dorsal midline to form the [[neural tube]].<ref>Brooker, R.J. 2014, Biology, 3rd edn, McGraw-Hill, New York, NY, 1084</ref> Subsequently, neural crest cells from the roof plate of the neural tube undergo an [[Epithelial-mesenchymal transition|epithelial to mesenchymal transition]], delaminating from the [[neuroepithelial cell|neuroepithelium]] and migrating through the periphery where they differentiate into varied cell types.<ref name=\"SJ04\"/> The emergence of neural crest was important in [[vertebrate]] evolution because many of its structural derivatives are defining features of the vertebrate [[clade]].<ref name=\"BF04\">{{cite journal | last1 = Meulemans | first1 = D. | last2 = Bronner-Fraser | first2 = M. | year = 2004 | title = Gene-regulatory interactions in neural crest evolution and development | url = | journal = Dev Cell | volume = 7 | issue = 3| pages = 291\u20139 | doi = 10.1016/j.devcel.2004.08.007 | pmid = 15363405 }}</ref> \n \nUnderlying the development of neural crest is a [[gene regulatory network]], described as a set of interacting signals, [[transcription factors]], and downstream [[effector (biology)|effector]] genes that confer cell characteristics such as multipotency and migratory capabilities.<ref name=\"BF07\">{{cite journal | last1 = Sauka-Spengler | first1 = T. | last2 = Meulemans | first2 = D. | last3 = Jones | first3 = M. | last4 = Bronner-Fraser | first4 = M. | year = 2007 | title = Ancient evolutionary origin of the neural crest gene regulatory network | url = | journal = Dev Cell | volume = 13 | issue = 3| pages = 405\u201320 | doi = 10.1016/j.devcel.2007.08.005 | pmid = 17765683 }}</ref> Understanding the molecular mechanisms of neural crest formation is important for our knowledge of human disease because of its contributions to multiple [[cell lineage]]s. Abnormalities in neural crest development cause [[neurocristopathy|neurocristopathies]], which include conditions such as [[frontonasal dysplasia]], [[Waardenburg\u2013Shah syndrome]], and [[DiGeorge syndrome]].<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>\n\nTherefore, defining the mechanisms of neural crest development may reveal key insights into vertebrate evolution and neurocristopathies.\n\n==History==\nNeural crest was first described in the chick embryo by [[Wilhelm His Sr.]] in 1868 as \"the cord in between\" (Zwischenstrang) because of its origin between the neural plate and non-neural ectoderm.<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>  He named the tissue ganglionic crest since its final destination was each lateral side of the neural tube where it differentiated into spinal ganglia.<ref name=\"douarin\">{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 2004 | title = The avian embryo as a model to study the development of the neural crest: a long and still ongoing story | url = | journal = Mech. Dev. | volume = 121 | issue = 9| pages = 1089\u2013102 | doi = 10.1016/j.mod.2004.06.003 | pmid = 15296974 }}</ref> During the first half of the 20th century the majority of research on neural crest was done using amphibian embryos which was reviewed by H\u00f6rstadius (1950) in a well known monograph.<ref>[[Sven H\u00f6rstadius|H\u00f6rstadius]], S. (1950). ''The Neural Crest: Its Properties and Derivatives in the Light of Experimental Research''. Oxford University Press, London, 111 p.</ref>\n \nCell labeling techniques advanced the field of neural crest because they allowed researchers to visualize the migration of the tissue throughout the developing embryos.  In the 1960s Weston and Chibon utilized radioisotopic labeling of the nucleus with tritiated thymidine in chick and amphibian embryo respectively.  However, this method suffers from drawbacks of stability, since every time the labeled cell divides the signal is diluted.  Modern cell labeling techniques such as rhodamine-lysinated dextran and the vital dye diI have also been developed to transiently mark neural crest lineages.<ref name=\"douarin\"/>\n\nThe quail-chick marking system, devised by Nicole Le Douarin in 1969, was another instrumental technique used to track neural crest cells.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 1969 | title = Particularit\u00e9s du noyau interphasique chez la Caille japonaise (Coturnix coturnix japonica). Utilisation de ces particularit\u00e9s comme \"marquage biologique\" dans les recherches sur les interactions tissulaires et les migrations cellulaires au cours de l'ontogen\u00e8se\" | url = | journal = Bull Biol Fr Belg | volume = 103 | issue = 3| pages = 435\u201352 | pmid = 4191116 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Le Douarin | first1 = N.M. | year = 1973 | title = A biological cell labeling technique and its use in experimental embryology | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 30 | issue = 1| pages = 217\u201322 | doi = 10.1016/0012-1606(73)90061-4 | pmid = 4121410 }}</ref> [[Chimera (genetics)|Chimera]]s, generated through transplantation, enabled researchers to distinguish neural crest cells of one species from the surrounding tissue of another species.  With this technique, generations of scientists were able to reliably mark and study the [[ontogeny]] of neural crest cells.\n\n==Induction==\nA molecular cascade of events is involved in establishing the migratory and multipotent characteristics of neural crest cells.  This [[gene regulatory network]] can be subdivided into the following four sub-networks described below.\n\n===Inductive signals===\nFirst, extracellular signaling molecules, secreted from the adjacent [[epidermis]] and underlying [[mesoderm]] such as [[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnts]], [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMPs]] and [[Fibroblast growth factor|Fgfs]] separate the non-neural [[ectoderm]] (epidermis) from the neural plate during [[neural induction]].<ref name=\"SJ04\"/><ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n\nWnt signaling has been demonstrated in neural crest induction in several species through gain-of-function and loss-of-function experiments. In coherence with this observation, the [[promoter (genetics)|promoter]] region of slug (a neural crest specific gene) contains a [[binding site]] for [[transcription factor]]s involved in the activation of Wnt-dependent target genes, suggestive of a direct role of Wnt signaling in neural crest specification.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vallin | first1 = J. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2001 | title = Cloning and characterization of the three Xenopus slug promoters reveal direct regulation by Lef/beta-catenin signaling | url = | journal = J Biol Chem | volume = 276 | issue = 32| pages = 30350\u20138 | doi = 10.1074/jbc.M103167200 | pmid=11402039}}</ref>\n\nThe current role of BMP in neural crest formation is associated with the induction of the neural plate.  BMP antagonists diffusing from the ectoderm generates a gradient of BMP activity. In this manner, the neural crest lineage forms from intermediate levels of BMP signaling required for the development of the neural plate (low BMP) and epidermis (high BMP).<ref name=\"SJ04\"/>\n\nFgf from the [[paraxial mesoderm]] has been suggested as a source of neural crest inductive signal.  Researchers have demonstrated that the expression of dominate-negative Fgf receptor in ectoderm explants blocks neural crest induction when recombined with paraxial mesoderm.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mayor | first1 = R. | last2 = Guerrero | first2 = N. | last3 = Martinez | first3 = C. | year = 1997 | title = Role of FGF and noggin in neural crest induction | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 189 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201312 | doi = 10.1006/dbio.1997.8634 | pmid = 9281332 }}</ref> The understanding of the role of BMP, Wnt, and Fgf pathways on neural crest specifier expression remains incomplete.\n\n===Neural plate border specifiers===\nSignaling events that establish the neural plate border lead to the expression of a set of transcription factors delineated here as neural plate border specifiers.  These molecules include Zic factors, Pax3/7, Dlx5, Msx1/2 which may mediate the influence of Wnts, BMPs, and Fgfs.  These genes are expressed broadly at the neural plate border region and precede the expression of bona fide neural crest markers.<ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n\nExperimental evidence places these transcription factors upstream of neural crest specifiers.  For example, in ''[[Xenopus]]'' Msx1 is [[necessary and sufficient]] for the expression of Slug, Snail, and FoxD3.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tribulo | first1 = C. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2003 | title = Regulation of Msx genes by Bmp gradient is essential for neural crest specification | url = | journal = Development | volume = 130 | issue = 26| pages = 6441\u201352 | doi = 10.1242/dev.00878 | pmid=14627721}}</ref> Furthermore, Pax3 is essential for FoxD3 expression in mouse embryos.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dottori | first1 = M. | last2 = Gross | first2 = M.K. | last3 = Labosky | first3 = P. | last4 = Goulding | first4 = M. | year = 2001 | title = The winged-helix transcription factor Foxd3 suppresses interneuron differentiation and promotes neural crest cell fate | url = | journal = Development | volume = 128 | issue = 21| pages = 4127\u20134138 | pmid = 11684651 }}</ref>\n\n===Neural crest specifiers===\nFollowing the expression of neural plate border specifiers is a collection of genes including Slug/Snail, FoxD3, Sox10, Sox9, AP-2 and c-Myc.  This suite of genes, designated here as neural crest specifiers, are activated in emergent neural crest cells.  At least in Xenopus, every neural crest specifier is necessary and/or sufficient for the expression of all other specifiers, demonstrating the existence of extensive cross-regulation.<ref name=\"BF04\"/> Moreover, this model organism was instrumental in the elucidation of the role of the Hedghehog signaling pathway in the specification of the neural crest, with the transcription factor Gli2 playing a key role.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cerrizuela|first=Santiago|last2=Vega-L\u00f3pez|first2=Guillermo A.|last3=Palacio|first3=Mar\u00eda Bel\u00e9n|last4=Tr\u00edbulo|first4=Celeste|last5=Aybar|first5=Manuel J.|date=2018-12-01|title=Gli2 is required for the induction and migration of Xenopus laevis neural crest|journal=Mechanisms of Development|volume=154|pages=219\u2013239|doi=10.1016/j.mod.2018.07.010|pmid=30086335|issn=0925-4773}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the tightly regulated network of neural crest specifiers are two other transcription factors Twist and Id.  Twist, a [[bHLH]] transcription factor, is required for mesenchyme differentiation of the [[pharyngeal arch]] structures.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Vincentz | first1 = J.W. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2008 | title = An absence of Twist1 results in aberrant cardiac neural crest morphogenesis | url = | journal = Dev Biol | volume = 320 | issue = 1| pages = 131\u20139 | doi = 10.1016/j.ydbio.2008.04.037 | pmid = 18539270 | pmc = 2572997 }}</ref> Id is a direct target of c-Myc and is known to be important for the maintenance of neural crest stem cells.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Light | first1 = W. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2005 | title = Xenopus Id3 is required downstream of Myc for the formation of multipotent neural crest progenitor cells | url = | journal = Development | volume = 132 | issue = 8| pages = 1831\u201341 | doi = 10.1242/dev.01734 | pmid=15772131}}</ref>\n\n===Neural crest effector genes===\nFinally, neural crest specifiers turn on the expression of effector genes, which confer certain properties such as migration and multipotency. Two neural crest effectors, ''[[Rho family of GTPases|Rho GTPases]]'' and ''[[cadherins]]'', function in delamination by regulating cell morphology and adhesive properties.  Sox9 and Sox10 regulate neural crest differentiation by activating many cell-type-specific effectors including Mitf, P0, Cx32, Trp and cKit.<ref name=\"BF04\"/>\n[[Image:GRN Crest.png|thumb|center|700px|alt=Neural Crest.|Putative neural crest gene-regulatory network functioning at the neural plate border in vertebrates. Red arrows represent proven direct regulatory interactions.  Black arrows show genetic interactions based on loss-of-function and gain-of-functions studies.  Gray lines denote repression.  Adapted from Bronner-Fraser 2004]]\n\n== Migration ==\n{{Further|Collective cell migration}}\n[[File:Neural Crest Cell Delamination .tif|thumb|Delamination of neural crest cells during development. Downregulation of CAMs and tight junction proteins is followed by secretion of MMPs and subsequent delamination.]]\nThe migration of neural crest cells involves a highly coordinated cascade of events that begins with closure of the [[Anatomical terms of location|dorsal]] [[neural tube]].\n\n=== Delamination ===\nAfter fusion of the [[neural fold]] to create the [[neural tube]], cells originally located in the [[neural plate]] border become neural crest [[Cell (biology)|cells]].<ref name=\":0\" /> For migration to begin, neural crest cells must undergo a process called delamination that involves a full or partial [[Epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT)]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Lamouille|first=Samy|year=2014|title=Molecular mechanisms of epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|pmc=4240281|journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology|volume=15|issue=3|pages=178\u2013196|pmid=24556840|doi=10.1038/nrm3758}}</ref> Delamination is defined as the separation of [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]] into different populations, in this case neural crest cells separating from the surrounding tissue.<ref name=\":1\" /> Conversely, EMT is a series of events coordinating a change from an [[Epithelium|epithelial]] to [[Mesenchymal stem cell|mesenchymal]] [[phenotype]].<ref name=\":4\" /> For example, delamination in [[Chicken|chick]] [[embryo]]s is triggered by a [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMP]]/[[Wnt signaling pathway|Wnt]] [[Signal transduction|cascade]] that induces the expression of EMT promoting [[transcription factor]]s such as [[SNAI2]] and [[FOXD3|FoxD3]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Although all neural crest cells undergo EMT, the timing of delamination occurs at different stages in different organisms: in [[African clawed frog|''Xenopus laevis'']] embryos there is a massive delamination that occurs when the [[neural plate]] is not entirely fused, whereas delamination in the [[Chicken|chick]] embryo occurs during fusion of the [[neural fold]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Theveneau|first=Eric|year=2012|title=Neural crest delamination and migration: From epithelium-to-mesenchyme transition to collective cell migration|journal=Developmental Biology|volume=366|issue=1|pages=34\u201354|doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2011.12.041|pmid=22261150|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1337167/2/1337167.pdf}}</ref>\n\nPrior to delamination, presumptive neural crest cells are initially anchored to neighboring cells by [[tight junction]] proteins such as [[occludin]] and [[cell adhesion molecule]]s such as [[Neural cell adhesion molecule|NCAM]] and [[CDH2|N''-''Cadherin]].<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Anatomical terms of location|Dorsally]] expressed [[Bone morphogenetic protein|BMPs]] initiate delamination by inducing the expression of the [[zinc finger]] protein transcription factors [[SNAI1|snail]], [[SNAI2|slug]], and [[Twist transcription factor|twist]].<ref name=\":0\" /> These factors play a direct role in inducing the [[Epithelial\u2013mesenchymal transition|epithelial-mesenchymal transition]] by reducing expression of [[occludin]] and [[CDH2|N-Cadherin]] in addition to promoting [[Post-translational modification|modification]] of [[Neural cell adhesion molecule|NCAMs]] with [[polysialic acid]] residues to decrease adhesiveness.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Neural crest cells also begin expressing [[protease]]s capable of degrading [[cadherin]]s such as [[ADAM10]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mayor|first=Roberto|year=2013|title=The Neural Crest|journal=Development|volume=140|issue=11|pages=2247\u20132251|doi=10.1242/dev.091751|pmid=23674598}}</ref> and secreting [[Matrix metalloproteinase|matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs)]] that degrade the overlying [[basal lamina]] of the neural tube to allow neural crest cells to escape.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, neural crest cells begin expressing [[integrin]]s that associate with [[extracellular matrix]] proteins, including [[collagen]], [[fibronectin]], and [[laminin]], during migration.<ref name=\":3\" /> Once the basal lamina becomes permeable the neural crest cells can begin migrating throughout the embryo.\n\n=== Migration ===\n[[File:Migration of Neural Crest Cells (v2).jpg|alt=|thumb|Migration of neural crest cells during development. Grey arrows indicate the direction of the paths crest cells migrate. (R=Rostral, C=Caudal)]]\nNeural crest cell migration occurs in a [[Anatomical terms of location|rostral]] to [[Anatomical terms of location|caudal]] direction without the need of a neuronal [[Scaffold/matrix attachment region|scaffold]] such as along a [[radial glial cell]]. For this reason the crest cell migration process is termed \u201cfree migration\u201d. Instead of scaffolding on [[progenitor cell]]s, neural crest migration is the result of repulsive guidance via [[EPHB3|EphB]]/[[Ephrin receptor|EphrinB]] and [[SEMA4D|semaphorin]]/[[neuropilin]]  signaling, interactions with the [[extracellular matrix]], and [[contact inhibition]] with one another.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Development of the Nervous System, 3rd ed|last=Sanes|first=Dan|publisher=ELSEVIER INC.|year=2012|isbn=978-0123745392|location=Oxford|pages=70\u201372}}</ref> While Ephrin and Eph proteins have the capacity to undergo bi-directional signaling, neural crest cell repulsion employs predominantly forward signaling to initiate a response within the [[Receptor (biochemistry)|receptor]] bearing neural crest cell.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Sakuka-Spengler|first=Tatjana|year=2008|title=A gene regulatory network orchestrates neural crest formation|doi=10.1038/nrm2428|pmid=18523435|journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology|volume=9|issue=7|pages=557\u2013568}}</ref> Burgeoning neural crest cells express EphB, a [[receptor tyrosine kinase]], which binds the EphrinB transmembrane [[Ligand (biochemistry)|ligand]] expressed in the caudal half of each [[somite]]. When these two domains interact it causes receptor tyrosine phosphorylation, activation of [[Rho family of GTPases|rhoGTPases]], and eventual [[Cytoskeleton|cytoskeletal]] rearrangements within the crest cells inducing them to repel. This phenomenon allows neural crest cells to funnel through the rostral portion of each somite.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSemaphorin-neuropilin repulsive signaling works synergistically with EphB signaling to guide neural crest cells down the rostral half of somites in mice. In chick embryos, semaphorin acts in the cephalic region to guide neural crest cells through the [[pharyngeal arch]]es. On top of repulsive repulsive signaling, neural crest cells express \u03b21and \u03b14 [[integrin]]s which allows for binding and guided interaction with [[collagen]], [[laminin]], and [[fibronectin]] of the extracellular matrix as they travel. Additionally, crest cells have intrinsic contact inhibition with one another while freely invading tissues of different origin such as [[mesoderm]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Neural crest cells that migrate through the rostral half of somites differentiate into [[Sensory neuron|sensory]] and [[Sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] neurons of the [[peripheral nervous system]]. The other main route neural crest cells take is [[Anatomical terms of location|dorsolaterally]] between the [[epidermis]] and the [[Dermatome (embryology)|dermamyotome]]. Cells migrating through this path differentiate into [[Melanocyte|pigment cells]] of the [[dermis]]. Further neural crest cell [[Cellular differentiation|differentiation]] and specification into their final cell type is biased by their [[Spatiotemporal gene expression|spatiotemporal]] subjection to morphogenic cues such as BMP, Wnt, FGF, [[Hox gene|Hox]], and [[Notch signaling pathway|Notch]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Principles of Neural Science|last=Kandel|first=Eric|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.|year=2013|isbn=978-0-07-139011-8|location=New York|pages=1197\u20131199}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical significance==\n[[Neurocristopathies]] result from the abnormal specification, migration, differentiation or death of neural crest cells throughout embryonic development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vega-Lopez|first=Guillermo A.|last2=Cerrizuela|first2=Santiago|last3=Tribulo|first3=Celeste|last4=Aybar|first4=Manuel J.|date=2018-12-01|title=Neurocristopathies: New insights 150 years after the neural crest discovery|journal=Developmental Biology|series=The Neural Crest: 150 years after His' discovery|volume=444|pages=S110\u2013S143|doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2018.05.013|pmid=29802835|issn=0012-1606}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bolande|first=Robert P.|date=1974-07-01|title=The neurocristopathies: A unifying concept of disease arising in neural crest maldevelopment|journal=Human Pathology|volume=5|issue=4|pages=409\u2013429|doi=10.1016/S0046-8177(74)80021-3|issn=0046-8177}}</ref> This group of diseases comprises a wide spectrum of congenital malformations affecting many newborns. Additionally, they arise because of genetic defects affecting the formation of neural crest and because of the action of [[Teratogen]]s <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cerrizuela|first=Santiago|last2=Vega\u2010Lopez|first2=Guillermo A.|last3=Aybar|first3=Manuel J.|date=2020-01-11|title=The role of teratogens in neural crest development|journal=Birth Defects Research|language=en|pages=bdr2.1644|doi=10.1002/bdr2.1644|pmid=31926062|issn=2472-1727}}</ref>\n\n====Waardenburg's syndrome====\n[[Waardenburg syndrome|Waardenburg's syndrome]] is a [[neurocristopathy]] that results from defective neural crest cell migration. The condition's main characteristics include [[piebaldism]] and [[Congenital hearing loss|congenital deafness]]. In the case of piebaldism, the colorless [[skin]] areas are caused by a total absence of neural crest-derived [[Biological pigment|pigment]]-producing [[melanocyte]]s.<ref name=\":x\">Mallory S.B., Wiener E, Nordlund J.J. (1986). \"Waardenburg\u2019s Syndrome with Hirschprung\u2019s Disease: A Neural Crest Defect.\" ''Pediatric Dermatology'' 3 (2): 119-124. {{PMID|3952027}}.</ref> There are four different types of Waardenburg's syndrome, each with distinct [[Genetics|genetic]] and physiological features. Types I and II are distinguished based on whether or not family members of the affected individual have [[Canthus#Pathology|dystopia canthorum]].<ref>Arias S (1971). \"Genetic heterogeneity in the Waardenburg's syndrome.\" ''Birth Defects'' B (4): 87-101. {{PMID|5006208}}.</ref> Type III gives rise to upper limb abnormalities. Lastly, type IV is also known as Waardenburg-Shah syndrome, and afflicted individuals display both Waardenburg's syndrome and [[Hirschsprung's disease]].<ref>\"Waardenburg syndrome\". Genetics Home Reference. October 2012.</ref> Types I and III are [[Heredity|inherited]] in an [[Genetic disorder#Autosomal dominant|autosomal dominant]] fashion,<ref name=\":x\" /> while II and IV exhibit an [[Genetic disorder#Autosomal recessive|autosomal recessive]] pattern of inheritance. Overall, Waardenburg's syndrome is rare, with an [[Incidence (epidemiology)|incidence]] of ~ 2/100,000 people in the United States. All [[Race (human categorization)|races]] and [[sex]]es are equally affected.<ref name=\":x\" /> There is no current cure or treatment for Waardenburg's syndrome.\n\n====Hirschsprung's Disease====\n\nAlso implicated in defects related to neural crest cell development and [[cellular migration|migration]] is [[Hirschsprung's disease]] (HD or HSCR), characterized by a lack of innervation in regions of the [[intestine]]. This lack of [[innervation]] can lead to further [[physiological]] abnormalities like an enlarged [[large intestine|colon]] ([[megacolon]]), obstruction of the [[bowels]], or even slowed growth. In healthy development, neural crest cells migrate into the [[gastrointestinal tract|gut]] and form the [[myenteric plexus|enteric ganglia]]. Genes playing a role in the healthy migration of these neural crest cells to the gut include [[RET proto-oncogene|RET]], [[GDNF]], [[GFR\u03b1]], [[EDN3]], and [[EDNRB]]. [[RET proto-oncogene|RET]], a [[receptor tyrosine kinase]] (RTK), forms a complex with [[GDNF]] and [[GFR\u03b1]]. [[EDN3]] and [[EDNRB]] are then implicated in the same signaling network. When this signaling is disrupted in mice, [[aganglionosis]], or the lack of these enteric ganglia occurs.<ref>Rogers, J. M. (2016). \"Search for the missing lncs: gene regulatory networks in neural crest development and long non-coding RNA biomarkers of Hirschsprung's disease.\" ''Neurogastroenterol Motil'' 28(2): 161-166.</ref>\n\n====Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder====\n\n[[Alcohol and Pregnancy|Prenatal alcohol exposure]] (PAE) is among the most common causes of [[Birth defect|developmental defects]].<ref>Sampson, P. D., Streissguth, A. P., Bookstein, F. L., Little, R. E., Clarren, S. K., Dehaene, P., Graham, J. M. Jr. (1997). The incidence of fetal alcohol syndrome and prevalence of the alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder ''Teratology'' 56(5), 317-326. {{DOI|10.1002/(SICI)1096-9926(199711)56:5<317::AID-TERA5>3.0.CO;2-U}}</ref> Depending on the extent of the exposure and the severity of the resulting abnormalities, [[patients]] are diagnosed within a continuum of disorders broadly labeled [[Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder]] (FASD). Severe FASD can impair neural crest [[Cell migration|migration]], as evidenced by characteristic [[craniofacial abnormalities]] including short [[palpebral fissures]], an elongated upper lip, and a smoothened [[philtrum]]. However, due to the promiscuous nature of [[ethanol]] [[Molecular binding|binding]], the mechanisms by which these abnormalities arise is still unclear. [[Cell culture]] [[Explant culture|explants]] of neural crest cells as well as [[in vivo]] developing [[zebrafish]] [[embryos]] exposed to ethanol show a decreased number of [[Cell Migration|migratory cells]] and decreased distances travelled by migrating neural crest cells. The mechanisms behind these changes are not well understood, but evidence suggests PAE can increase [[apoptosis]] due to increased [[cytosol]]ic [[calcium]] levels caused by [[Inositol trisphosphate|IP3]]-mediated [[Calcium signalling|release of calcium]] from [[intracellular]] stores. It has also been proposed that the decreased viability of ethanol-exposed neural crest cells is caused by increased [[oxidative stress]]. Despite these, and other advances much remains to be discovered about how ethanol affects neural crest development. For example, it appears that ethanol differentially affects certain neural crest cells over others; that is, while craniofacial abnormalities are common in PAE, neural crest-derived [[Melanocyte|pigment cells]] appear to be minimally affected.<ref>Smith, S. M., Garic, A., Flentke, G. R., & Berres, M. E. (2014). Neural crest development in fetal alcohol syndrome. ''Birth Defects Res C Embryo Today'', 102(3), 210-220. {{DOI|10.1002/bdrc.21078}}</ref>\n\n====DiGeorge syndrome====\n[[DiGeorge syndrome]] is associated with [[Deletion (genetics)|deletions]] or [[translocations]] of a small segment in the [[human]] [[chromosome 22]]. This deletion may disrupt rostral neural crest [[cell migration]] or [[Human embryonic development|development]]. Some defects observed are linked to the [[pharyngeal pouch (embryology)|pharyngeal pouch]] system, which receives contribution from rostral migratory crest cells. The [[symptoms]] of DiGeorge syndrome include [[congenital heart defects]], [[birth defects|facial defects]], and some [[neurological]] and [[learning disabilities]]. Patients with 22q11 deletions have also been reported to have higher incidence of [[schizophrenia]] and [[bipolar disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scambler | first1 = Peter J. | year = 2000 | title = The 22q11 deletion syndromes | url = | journal = Human Molecular Genetics | volume = 9 | issue = 16| pages = 2421\u20132426 | pmid = 11005797 }}</ref>\n\n====Treacher Collins Syndrome====\n[[Treacher Collins Syndrome]] (TCS) results from the compromised development of the first and second [[pharyngeal arches]] during the early embryonic stage, which ultimately leads to mid and lower face abnormalities. TCS is caused by the [[missense mutation]] of the [[TCOF1]] gene, which causes neural crest cells to undergo [[apoptosis]] during [[embryogenesis]]. Although [[mutations]] of the TCOF1 gene are among the best characterized in their role in TCS, mutations in [[POLR1C]] and [[POLR1D]] [[genes]] have also been linked to the [[pathogenesis]] of TCS.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ahmed | first1 = M. | last2 = Ye | first2 = X. | last3 = Taub | first3 = P. | year = 2016 | title = Review of the Genetic Basis of Jaw Malformations | url = http://doi.org/10.1055/s-0036-1593505 | journal = Journal of Pediatric Genetics | volume = 05 | issue = 04| pages = 209\u2013219 }}</ref>\n\n==Cell lineages==\nNeural crest cells originating from different positions along the [[anterior]]-posterior axis develop into various tissues.  These regions of neural crest can be divided into four main functional domains, which include the cranial neural crest, trunk neural crest, vagal and sacral neural crest, and cardiac neural crest.\n\n===Cranial neural crest===\n{{Main|cranial neural crest}}\n\nCranial neural crest migrates dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various cranial ganglia and craniofacial cartilages and bones.<ref name=\":5\">Taneyhill, L.A. (2008). \"To adhere or not to adhere: the role of Cadherins in neural crest development\". Cell Adh Migr. 2, 223\u201330.</ref> These cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they contribute to the [[thymus]], bones of the middle ear and jaw and the [[odontoblasts]] of the tooth primordia.<ref name=\"gilbert\">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/bookshelf/br.fcgi?book=dbio&part=A3109#A3133</ref>\n\n===Trunk neural crest===\n{{Main|trunk neural crest}}\n\nTrunk neural crest gives rise  two populations of cells.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vega-Lopez|first=Guillermo A.|last2=Cerrizuela|first2=Santiago|last3=Aybar|first3=Manuel J.|date=2017|title=Trunk neural crest cells: formation, migration and beyond|journal=The International Journal of Developmental Biology|language=en|volume=61|issue=1\u20132|pages=5\u201315|doi=10.1387/ijdb.160408gv|pmid=28287247|issn=0214-6282}}</ref>  One group of cells fated to become [[melanocytes]] migrates dorsolaterally into the ectoderm towards the ventral midline.  A second group of cells migrates ventrolaterally through the anterior portion of each [[sclerotome]].  The cells that stay in the sclerotome form the [[dorsal root ganglion|dorsal root ganglia]], whereas those that continue more ventrally form the sympathetic ganglia, [[adrenal medulla]], and the nerves surrounding the aorta.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\n\n===Vagal and sacral neural crest===\nThe vagal and sacral neural crest cells develop into the ganglia of the [[enteric nervous system]] and the parasympathetic ganglia.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\n\n===Cardiac neural crest===\n{{Main|cardiac neural crest}}\n\n[[Cardiac neural crest cells|Cardiac neural crest]] develops into melanocytes, cartilage, connective tissue and neurons of some pharyngeal arches.  Also, this domain gives rise to regions of the heart such as the musculo-connective tissue of the large arteries, and part of the [[septum]], which divides the pulmonary circulation from the aorta.<ref name=\"gilbert\"/>\nThe semilunar valves of the heart are associated with neural crest cells according to new research.<ref>{{cite journal | doi=10.1007/BF00185519 | volume=182 | issue=3 | title=Association of cephalic neural crest cells with cardiovascular development, particularly that of the semilunar valves | year=1990 | journal=Anatomy and Embryology | last1 = Takamura | first1 = Kazushi | last2 = Okishima | first2 = Takahiro | last3 = Ohdo | first3 = Shozo | last4 = Hayakawa | first4 = Kunio| pages=263\u201372 | pmid=2268069 }}</ref>\n\n==Evolution==\nSeveral structures that distinguish the vertebrates from other chordates are formed from the derivatives of neural crest cells.  In their \"New head\" theory, Gans and Northcut argue that the presence of neural crest was the basis for vertebrate specific features, such as sensory ganglia and cranial skeleton.  Furthermore, the appearance of these features was pivotal in vertebrate evolution because it enabled a predatory lifestyle.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gans | first1 = C. | last2 = Northcutt | first2 = R. G. | year = 1983 | title = Neural crest and the origin of vertebrates: A new head | url = | journal = Science | volume = 220 | issue = 4594| pages = 268\u2013274 | doi = 10.1126/science.220.4594.268 | pmid = 17732898 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Northcutt | first = Glenn | year = 2005 | title = The new head hypothesis revisited | journal =  Journal of Experimental Zoology Part B: Molecular and Developmental Evolution | volume = 304B | issue = 4| pages = 274\u2013297 | doi = 10.1002/jez.b.21063 | pmid = 16003768 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, considering the neural crest a vertebrate innovation does not mean that it arose ''[[wikt:de novo|de novo]]''. Instead, new structures often arise through modification of existing developmental regulatory programs.  For example, regulatory programs may be changed by the [[exaptation|co-option]] of new upstream regulators or by the employment of new downstream gene targets, thus placing existing networks in a novel context.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Sauka-Spengler | first1 = T. | last2 = Bronner-Fraser | first2 = M. | year = 2006 | title = Development and evolution of the migratory neural crest: a gene regulatory perspective | url = | journal = Curr Opin Genet Dev | volume = 13 | issue = 4| pages = 360\u20136 | doi = 10.1016/j.gde.2006.06.006 | pmid = 16793256 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Donoghue | first1 = P.C. | last2 = Graham | first2 = A. | last3 = Kelsh | first3 = R.N. | year = 2008 | title = The origin and evolution of the neural crest | url = | journal = BioEssays | volume = 30 | issue = 6| pages = 530\u201341 | doi = 10.1002/bies.20767 | pmid = 18478530 | pmc = 2692079 }}</ref> This idea is supported by [[in situ hybridization]] data that shows the conservation of the neural plate border specifiers in [[protochordate]]s, which suggest that part of the neural crest precursor network was present in a common ancestor to the chordates.<ref name=\"BF07\"/> In some non-vertebrate chordates such as [[tunicates]] a lineage of cells (melanocytes) has been identified, which are similar to neural crest cells in vertebrates. This implies that a rudimentary neural crest existed in a common ancestor of vertebrates and tunicates.<ref name=Abitua2012>{{Cite journal | last1 = Abitua | first1 = P. B. | last2 = Wagner | first2 = E. | last3 = Navarrete | first3 = I. A. | last4 = Levine | first4 = M. | title = Identification of a rudimentary neural crest in a non-vertebrate chordate | doi = 10.1038/nature11589 | journal = Nature | year = 2012 | pmid =  23135395| pmc = 4257486| volume=492 | issue = 7427 | pages=104\u2013107}}</ref>\n\n==Neural crest derivatives==\n'''Ectomesenchyme (also known as Mesectoderm)''':<ref>Kalcheim, C. and Le Douarin, N. M. (1998). The Neural Crest (2nd ed.). Cambridge, U. K.: Cambridge University Press.</ref> [[odontoblasts]], [[dental papilla]]e, the [[chondrocranium]] ([[nasal capsule]], [[Meckel's cartilage]], [[scleral ossicles]], quadrate, articular, hyoid and columella), [[trachea]]l and [[larynx|laryngeal]] cartilage, the [[dermatocranium]] (membranous bones), dorsal fins and the turtle plastron (lower vertebrates), [[pericyte]]s and smooth muscle of branchial arteries and veins, [[tendons]] of ocular and masticatory muscles, [[connective tissue]] of head and neck glands (pituitary, salivary, lachrymal, thymus, thyroid) [[dermis]] and adipose tissue of calvaria, ventral neck and face\n\n'''Endocrine cells''':\n[[chromaffin cell]]s of the adrenal medulla, [[glomus cell]]s type I/II.\n\n'''Peripheral nervous system''':\n[[Sensory neuron]]s and glia of the [[dorsal root ganglia]], cephalic ganglia (VII and in part, V, IX, and X), [[Rohon-Beard cell]]s, some [[Merkel cell]]s in the whisker,<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 19786578 | doi=10.1083/jcb.200907080 | volume=187 | issue=1 | title=Epidermal progenitors give rise to Merkel cells during embryonic development and adult homeostasis | pmc=2762088 | date=October 2009 | journal=J. Cell Biol. | pages=91\u2013100 | last1 = Van Keymeulen | first1 = A | last2 = Mascre | first2 = G | last3 = Youseff | first3 = KK | display-authors = etal  }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 12645929 | volume=253 | issue=2 | title=Neural crest origin of mammalian Merkel cells | date=January 2003 | journal=Dev. Biol. | pages=258\u201363 | last1 = Szeder | first1 = V | last2 = Grim | first2 = M | last3 = Halata | first3 = Z | last4 = Sieber-Blum | first4 = M | doi=10.1016/s0012-1606(02)00015-5}}</ref> \n[[Satellite glial cell]]s of all autonomic and sensory ganglia, [[Schwann cell|Schwann]] cells of all peripheral nerves.\n\n'''Enteric cells''':\n[[Enterochromaffin cells]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lake|first1=JI|last2=Heuckeroth|first2=RO|title=Enteric nervous system development: migration, differentiation, and disease.|journal=American Journal of Physiology. Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology|date=1 July 2013|volume=305|issue=1|pages=G1\u201324|pmid=23639815|doi=10.1152/ajpgi.00452.2012|pmc=3725693}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Melanocyte]]s and iris muscle and pigment cells''', and even associated with some tumors (such as [[melanotic neuroectodermal tumor of infancy]]).\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[First arch syndrome]]\n* [[DGCR2]]\u2014may control neural crest cell migration\n*[[List of human cell types derived from the germ layers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{EmbryologyUNSW|Notes/ncrest}}\n* {{BrainInfo|ancil|445}}\n* [http://www.med.umich.edu/lrc/coursepages/M1/embryology/embryo/images/neural_crest_and_notocord.gif Diagram] at [[University of Michigan]]\n* [http://www.palaeos.com/Vertebrates/Bones/Teeth/Images/ChickNeural%20Crest.gif Hox domains in chicks]\n\n{{embryology}}\n{{Development of nervous system}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Embryology of nervous system]]\n[[Category:Ectoderm]]\n[[Category:Chordates]]\n[[Category:Chordate anatomy]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 6 DOIs, templated 4 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_crest"}
